body_html: @siddharth-agrawal One recent example is the introduction of tf.sparse_softmax() here. The Python wrapper in sparse_ops.py -- named sparse_softmax() and which accepts one input -- overrides the function gen_sparse_ops.sparse_softmax(), which accepts three inputs. This is what I meant by overriding. Does this make sense?

body: @siddharth-agrawal One recent example is the introduction of `tf.sparse_softmax()` [here](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/7e5261b7f35871282010f655de5d72e2d2edc29f).  The Python wrapper in `sparse_ops.py` -- named `sparse_softmax()` and which accepts one input -- overrides the function `gen_sparse_ops.sparse_softmax()`, which accepts three inputs.  This is what I meant by overriding.  Does this make sense?
